{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "3. Extension Points: Modularity & Pluggability",
  "description": "Where collaborators can plug in their own modules (a new backend adapter, a new TTS engine), how the two real extension points are shaped, and ŌĆö just as important ŌĆö which modules are deliberately NOT pluggable and why, so effort isn't wasted fighting the existing design. Companion to '1. Architecture & Data Flow'.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "title": "Start here",
      "description": "**Only two things in this codebase are actually designed to be pluggable: the backend adapter and the TTS engine.** Everything else ŌĆö audio capture/playback, VAD, STT, safeword detection ŌĆö is a single concrete class with no interface, on purpose.\n\nThat's a deliberate, hard-won design choice, not an oversight: an earlier related project (`voice-opencode`) built a multi-engine STT/TTS factory with cloud fallback *before* a single local engine actually worked end to end ŌĆö pluggability was built before there was anything real to abstract over. See `README.md` ŌåÆ \"Lessons from an earlier attempt\" for the full story.\n\nSo: this tour shows you exactly where to plug in, using the two `ABC`s that exist specifically because multiple implementations were anticipated ŌĆö and calls out where NOT to add one."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/adapters/base.py",
      "line": 32,
      "pattern": "class BackendAdapter\\(ABC\\):",
      "description": "**Extension point 1: `BackendAdapter`.** One implementation per target CLI. Today: OpenCode. Documented as intended, not yet built: Claude Code, Codex.\n\nThe contract is 5 methods: `send_text`, `send_interject`, `send_hard_stop`, `is_busy`, `events`. Read the class docstring here carefully before implementing a new one ŌĆö it's not just a method list, it draws hard semantic lines (interject vs. hard-stop must never collapse into one \"interrupt\" concept) and an honesty clause about what `send_hard_stop` can actually guarantee if the target backend has no real cancel endpoint.\n\n**Correction (see `OPENCODE_API_NOTES.md`):** the concrete example that honesty clause points to (`OpenCodeAdapter`, next step) turned out to be wrong about OpenCode having no cancel endpoint ŌĆö a real one exists, the adapter just wasn't built against the real API. The general principle in this docstring still holds; the specific example doesn't."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/adapters/opencode.py",
      "line": 27,
      "pattern": "class OpenCodeAdapter\\(BackendAdapter\\):",
      "description": "**A reference implementation ŌĆö but a wrong one. Read `OPENCODE_API_NOTES.md` before copying this pattern.** `OpenCodeAdapter` targets `POST /api/sessions`, `GET /api/sessions/:id/events`, `POST /api/sessions/:id/messages` ŌĆö inferred from an earlier related project's documentation, never verified against a real server. Testing against an actual `opencode serve` instance (2026-07-10) found the real API uses different, singular paths (`/session`, `/session/:id/message`, `/session/:id/event`), a completely different message body shape (a `parts` array, not `{messages: [...]}`), a real `/session/:id/abort` endpoint this code claims doesn't exist, and a much richer ~28-type event model instead of this code's flat 5-value enum.\n\n**The shape of the pattern is still right** ŌĆö thin typed client, `_ensure_session`/`_post_message`/`events()` as the structure, `warn_if_insecure` for network backends ŌĆö copy that. Just don't trust this file's actual endpoint paths or body shapes as ground truth; verify against whatever real API your new adapter targets, the way this investigation verified (and corrected) this one."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/config.py",
      "line": 39,
      "pattern": "class BackendConfig\\(BaseModel\\):",
      "description": "**The config-side selector ŌĆö now wired.** `BackendConfig.name` (default \"opencode\") selects which adapter `create_backend_adapter()` (in `adapters/__init__.py`) constructs ŌĆö `OpenCodeAdapter` today, raising a clear `ValueError` for anything else rather than silently doing nothing. If you're adding a second adapter, add its branch there."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/tts/base.py",
      "line": 24,
      "pattern": "class TTSEngine\\(ABC\\):",
      "description": "**Extension point 2: `TTSEngine`.** One implementation per local TTS backend. Today: Piper. Named as a future candidate in `README.md` ŌåÆ Component software: Kokoro.\n\nThe contract: `sample_rate` (property), `synthesize_stream` (the one concrete engines must implement), `stop`, `is_speaking`. Read the docstring here too ŌĆö it states a hard requirement: **every concrete engine must call `sanitize_text` before synthesizing**, since the input text originates from untrusted LLM output. That's not optional style guidance, it's the security boundary this whole TTS layer exists to enforce (see the '2. Review Findings' tour for why)."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/tts/piper.py",
      "line": 16,
      "pattern": "class PiperTTSEngine\\(TTSEngine\\):",
      "description": "**The reference implementation ŌĆö your template for a new TTS engine.** Notice the shape a new engine (e.g. Kokoro) would need to match: load whatever voice/model once at construction, expose `sample_rate` from it, and implement `synthesize_stream` as a true async generator ŌĆö bridging a blocking/sync synthesis call through a background thread + queue if the underlying library isn't natively async (see `synthesize_stream` a bit further down, and the '1. Architecture & Data Flow' tour for why that bridge pattern matters for time-to-first-audio)."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/config.py",
      "line": 29,
      "pattern": "class TTSConfig\\(BaseModel\\):",
      "description": "**Same selector, now wired on the TTS side too.** `TTSConfig.engine` (default \"piper\") selects which engine `create_tts_engine()` (in `tts/__init__.py`) constructs. Also fixed along the way: this config used to declare `voice`/`rate`/`volume` fields that didn't match `PiperTTSEngine`'s real constructor at all ŌĆö replaced with `model_path`/`config_path`, which actually correspond to what the engine takes."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/orchestrator/orchestrator.py",
      "line": 30,
      "pattern": "tts: TTSEngine \\| None = None,",
      "description": "**The extension point that actually works today, proven by tests.** `Orchestrator` takes `tts`/`player` as optional constructor arguments ŌĆö plain dependency injection, no factory needed here. Anything satisfying the `TTSEngine` ABC (or, for `player`, a real `AudioPlayer` subclass ŌĆö see the next step for why that one isn't an ABC) can be passed in without touching a single line of `Orchestrator`'s internals.\n\nThis is exactly how the test suite substitutes fakes for real audio hardware ŌĆö not a theoretical claim, see the next step."
    },
    {
      "file": "tests/test_orchestrator.py",
      "line": 40,
      "pattern": "class FakeTTSEngine\\(TTSEngine\\):",
      "description": "**Proof the injection point works.** `FakeTTSEngine` is a real subclass of the `TTSEngine` ABC (it has to be ŌĆö mypy rejects a duck-typed stand-in, see `TESTING.md` ŌåÆ Type checking) substituted straight into `Orchestrator`'s constructor in place of `PiperTTSEngine`. No real audio hardware, no model downloads, and the orchestrator's routing/speaking logic is exercised exactly as it would be with a real engine.\n\n`FakePlayer` a few lines down does the same for `AudioPlayer` ŌĆö but subclasses the concrete class rather than an ABC, since `AudioPlayer` has none (see the next two steps for why that's deliberate, not a gap to fix)."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/audio/capture.py",
      "line": 21,
      "pattern": "class MicrophoneStream:",
      "description": "**What's deliberately NOT pluggable, part 1.** `MicrophoneStream` (and `AudioPlayer`, `UtteranceSegmenter`, `LocalTranscriber`, `SafewordDetector` ŌĆö none of them) has no ABC, no factory, no \"engine\" config field. Each is a single concrete class doing one job.\n\nThis is a design choice, not a TODO: this codebase currently needs exactly one working implementation per role, and building a plugin abstraction for a role with only one real implementation adds real complexity (an interface to maintain, a factory to keep in sync, a config schema to reconcile) for zero present benefit. If you have a second real, working implementation of one of these (a different VAD library, a Windows-native audio backend, etc.), that's the moment to introduce an ABC here ŌĆö not before."
    },
    {
      "title": "Adding a new adapter or TTS engine: checklist",
      "description": "**New `BackendAdapter`** (e.g. Claude Code, Codex):\n1. Subclass `BackendAdapter`, implement all 5 methods against that tool's actual headless/structured interface.\n2. Be honest in `send_hard_stop`'s docstring about what it can/can't guarantee ŌĆö don't copy `OpenCodeAdapter`'s current claim that no cancel endpoint exists as a pattern; that claim is itself now known to be wrong for OpenCode (see `OPENCODE_API_NOTES.md`). Verify against the real target API instead of inferring from docs.\n3. Add a factory (`BackendConfig.name -> AdapterClass`) if one still doesn't exist by the time you do this.\n4. Test against a real server over a real loopback socket, the way `tests/test_opencode_adapter.py` does ŌĆö not just mocks of your own HTTP client, and ideally against the real running service too, not just a fake server that mirrors your own assumptions (that's exactly how `OpenCodeAdapter`'s wrong API shape went undetected for as long as it did).\n\n**New `TTSEngine`** (e.g. Kokoro):\n1. Subclass `TTSEngine`, implement `sample_rate` and `synthesize_stream`.\n2. Call `sanitize_text` on the input **before** synthesizing ŌĆö non-negotiable, see step 5 of this tour.\n3. If the underlying library's synthesis call is blocking/sync, bridge it through a background thread + queue the way `PiperTTSEngine` does ŌĆö don't buffer the whole response before yielding anything (see the '2. Review Findings' tour for why that was a real, measured regression when it happened here).\n4. Test with a fake voice object (see `tests/test_tts.py`'s `_FakeVoice`) ŌĆö no real model download needed for unit tests.\n\nFor either: run `pytest tests/` and `mypy src/ scripts/ tests/ --ignore-missing-imports` (see `TESTING.md`) before considering it done."
    }
  ]
}
